  "summary": {
    "as": "Introduced in House",
    "asOf": "2023-03-23",
    "date": "2023-12-06T17:37:16Z",
    "text": "Stopping Illicit Fentanyl Trafficking Act of 2023 or the SIFT Act of 2023\n\nThis bill permanently adds five fentanyl analogues and the entire category of fentanyl-related substances to schedule I of the Controlled Substances Act. A schedule I controlled substance is a drug, substance, or chemical that has a high potential for abuse; has no currently accepted medical value; and is subject to regulatory controls and administrative, civil, and criminal penalties under the Controlled Substances Act.\n\nFentanyl-related substances are currently regulated under schedule I through a temporary order issued by the Drug Enforcement Administration. The temporary order expires on December 31, 2024.\n\nThe bill also creates a process to remove from schedule I certain fentanyl-related substances that do not have a high potential for abuse."
  },
